examplars:
1. think about the different groups of people who live in the local community (your village, town, city or district);
2. share ideas they have about the history of the people (including where they came from, the leaders who brought them, how the village started);
3. share stories that describe the culture or way of life (including their language, the food they eat, their dressing, type of buildings, farming tools, way of cooking, body marks, songs, dances, artworks) of people in the community;
4. listen to and ask questions about stories told by community elders or resource persons that explain the history and culture of the people in the community;
5. take a walk in the community to visit famous buildings (such as the post office, chief's palace, old buildings), important places and old sites of the community. Where possible, view photographs or use ICT devices (such as computer) to view pictures or watch videos of artworks on the internet;
6. use ideas gained to plan to create own visual artworks that describe the people and how they live describe who the people are and how they live.

1. think about visual artworks (including drawings, clay pots, posters, wood carvings, calendars) they know of or have seen in the community;
2. look at photographs or pictures that show artworks in books, catalogues, magazines and identify them by name or what they are made of or used for;
3. identify and share ideas about different kinds of visual artworks that are produced or found in the local community;
4. visit the workplace of a visual artist (graphic designer making prints on T-shirts, pottery artist making clay pots, textile artist weaving Kente, sculptor making cement statue, etc.) to observe, ask questions, make notes and learn about their work practices;
5. record knowledge gained for planning own visual artworks.

1. show knowledge about natural things (e.g. stone, wood, feather);
2. describe what makes up the natural environment (e.g. plants, rivers, animals, clouds). Where possible, use ICT devices to watch videos on the natural environment;
3. take out-of-classroom walk to observe natural objects in the surroundings and collect samples and/or take photographs;
4. organise the sample of natural objects and study their features variety of colours, shapes, size, etc. observed in them;
5. organise the sample of natural objects collected to create a 'natural learning corner' in the classroom;
6. share ideas about the sample of natural objects;
7. develop ideas for drawing and colouring pictures, modelling;
8. consider the features of the things observed in the natural environment, e.g. beauty, size, smoothness, roughness, hardness, softness, how shiny, variety, repetition, weight, space, shape, form, line, colour, texture).

1. reflect on conditions in the local community and identify topical issues (e.g. choked gutters, flooding, road safety) of concern to the people;
2. talk about the causes of the local topical issues (e.g. plastic materials, sand winning, buildings on water ways) in the local community;
3. share ideas on how the features of any local visual artwork reflect any topical issue experienced in the community;
4. explore how topical issues can influence the making of visual artworks;
5. use knowledge gained to make decisions for improvising own visual artworks that express their views of topical issues experienced in the community.

1. think about the different groups of people who live in the local community (your village, town, city or district);
2. share ideas they have about the history of the people (including where they came from, the leaders who brought them, how the village started);
3. share stories that describe the culture or way of life (including their language, the food they eat, their dressing, type of buildings, farming tools, way of cooking, body marks, songs, dances, artworks) of people in the community;
4. listen to and ask questions on stories told by community elders or resource persons that explain the history and culture of the people in the community;
5. take a walk in the community to visit famous buildings (such as the post office, chief's palace, old buildings), important places and old sites of the community. Where possible, view photographs or use ICT devices (such as computer) to view pictures or watch videos on the internet;
6. use ideas gained to plan to create own performing artworks that describe the people and how they live.

1. think about performing artworks (music, dance, drama, poetry) they know of or have seen produced or performed in the local community;
2. look at photographs or pictures or watch videos that show different music, dance and drama performances and identify them by name or talk about how these performing artworks are produced or used for in the community;
3. share and act familiar music, dance and drama in the local community;
4. identify and share ideas about different kinds of performing artworks that are produced or performed in the local community;
5. visit the workplace of a performing artist (e.g. musician, dancer, poet, choreographer) to observe, ask questions, make notes and learn about their instruments and work practices;
6. record knowledge gained for improvising own performing artworks.

1. show knowledge about natural things or objects (e.g. stone, wood, feather);
2. describe what makes up the natural environment (e.g. plants, rivers, animals, clouds). Where possible, use ICT devices to watch videos on the natural environment;
3. take out-of-classroom walks to observe natural things and objects in the local surroundings and collect samples and/or take photographs or make videos of the natural environment;
4. organise samples of natural objects collected to create a 'natural learning corner' in the classroom;
5. observe the natural objects carefully and talk about their features (e.g. colour, shape, size, smoothness, roughness, weight, sound they make, movements);
6. share ideas about how any of the natural objects collected can be used to produce or perform music, dance or drama in the local community;
7. use ideas gained to improvise own performing artworks that express knowledge of the natural environment.

1. reflect on conditions in the local community and identify topical issues (e.g. choked gutters, flooding, road safety) of concern to the people;
2. talk about the causes of these local issues (e.g. plastic materials, sand winning, buildings on water ways) in the local community;
3. share ideas on how the features of any local music, dance or drama reflect any topical issue experienced in the community;
4. explore how topical issues can promote the making of performing artworks;
5. use knowledge gained to improvise own performing artworks that express own views on topical issues experienced in the community.

1. refresh their memory on visual artworks that are produced or found in the local community;
2. recall all kinds of visual artworks that reflect the history and culture of the people;
3. make decisions on how the artworks (e.g. drawing, poster, clay, modelling) they plan to make will reflect the history and culture or way of life of people in the local community.

1. develop own ideas on the nature of visual artworks produced or found in the local community (e.g. clay pots, baskets, carvings, beads);
2. make decisions on tools, materials and visual arts making methods that are suitable for making those artworks;
3. plan how the choice of artworks will be made to express the history and culture/way of life of people in the local community;
4. make pencil and crayon doodles/scribbles/outlines to define the choice of artworks they have in mind.

1. recall ideas gathered on the making and use of visual artworks that are produced or found in the local community;
2. refine own ideas on visual art making tools, materials and methods used by the local artists;
3. organise and develop own ideas, knowledge an understanding of what makes up the natural and man-made environment;
4. make pencil/crayon outlines to define the artworks they plan to make to reflect the natural and man-made environments.

1. recall from memory what current issues are of concern to people in the local community;
2. recall the selection of local artworks that reflect current topical issues of concern to the local community;
3. make pencil/crayon outlines to define the artworks they plan to make to reflect the topical local issues.

1. refresh their memory on music, dance and drama that are produced or found in the local community;
2. recall all kinds of music, dance, drama that reflect the history and culture of the people;
3. make decisions on how the performing artworks they plan to make or perform will reflect the history and culture or way of life of the people.

1. develop ideas on the nature of performing artworks (music, dance and drama) produced or performed in the local community;
2. make decisions on instruments, resources and techniques that are suitable for making these performing artworks;
3. plan how the choice performing artworks will be made to express the history and culture or way of life of people in the local community;
4. Record ideas to define the choice of artworks they have in mind.

1. recall ideas gathered on the making and use of the music, dance and drama artworks in the local community;
2. refine own ideas on the instruments, resources and methods used by local performing artists;
3. organise and develop own ideas on what makes up the natural and manmade environments;
4. plan for making own performing artworks that will reflect the natural and manmade environments of the local community.

1. recall from memory what current issues are of concern to people in the local community;
2. recall the selection of local performing artworks that reflect these topical issues in the local community;
3. define the artworks they plan to make that will reflect these local topical issues.

1. make artworks to reflect some topical issues in the local community;
2. make own drawings and colour them to educate the local community on those topical issues;
3. select and use suitable and appropriate materials available (e.g. clay for modelling and casting; paper for drawing and painting; colour for painting; glue for bonding);
4. select and use suitable and appropriate tools and equipment available (e.g. brush for painting; scissors and cutting knives for cutting);
5. select and use suitable and appropriate methods of production (e.g. painting, printing, weaving, knotting, trimming, doodling, modelling, casting, carving, construction, assemblage, folding, quilling);
6. select and use suitable and appropriate manual/mechanical finishing and decorating techniques (e.g. firing, painting, burnishing, spraying).

1. perform own music, dance and drama that reflect the identified topical issues in the local community;
2. make other performing artworks to educate the people on the effects of those local topical issues;
3. select and use suitable and appropriate instruments, elements, resources, equipment available (e.g. drums, flutes, bells, shakers, rasps, xylophones, finger pianos, rattles, clappers, castanets, horns, whistles, harps, costumes, props);
4. select and use suitable and appropriate manual/mechanical/electronic production methods/techniques (e.g. voice, gestures, movements, language, improvisation, imitation, adaptation and guided writing skills to communicate feelings, melodic, rhythmic, harmonic and dynamic elements and dramatization);
5. select/create props, scenery, and costumes for different styles and performances which support and enhance the intent of a production;
6. Demonstrate basic knowledge and skills in the use and application of the elements and principles of design, instruments, methods and techniques freely in creative and expressive ways to produce own music, dance and drama.

1. watch a short video on an exhibition or visit an exhibition centre or gallery;
2. discuss the need for displaying portfolio of own visual artworks;
3. plan a display of own portfolio of visual artworks (e.g. drawings, colour work, patterns) to share, educate and inform the public on the history and culture of people in the local community.

1. talk about how to display artworks (e.g. by hanging, draping and spreading);
2. plan the arrangement of own artworks to share, educate and inform the public on the topical issues of the local community;
3. discuss the need for displaying portfolio of own and/or others visual artworks;
4. develop a roadmap for the exhibition by fixing a date, selecting a venue, inviting an audience;
5. select and agree on a theme for the exhibition by brainstorming, discussing and reaching a consensus;
6. send manual and/or electronic invitations (e.g. letters, announcements, posters, and jingles) to target audience;
7. select works for the exhibition by considering criteria such as creativity and originality, finishing and decoration, relevance of the works to the theme, social and cultural importance, mode of display: hanging, draping, spreading;
8. getting ready: plan the layout of the exhibition, prepare labels for the works (e.g. title, name of artist, date), clean and tidy up the exhibition hall and environment;
9. post exhibition/display activities: cleaning, appreciation, appraisal, evaluation, reporting etc.

1. watch a short video or live performances that reflect the history and culture of the people in Ghana;
2. discuss the need for displaying portfolio of own performing artworks;
3. plan a display of portfolio of own music, dance and drama compositions to share, educate and inform the public on the history and culture of people in the local community.

1. watch a short video that reflect the natural and manmade environments in the local community;
2. select compositions according to factors such as creativity and originality;
3. plan the arrangement of own music, dance and drama to share own views on the natural and manmade environments of the local community.

1. watch a short video that reflects topical issues in the local community;
2. plan a display of own music, dance and drama to educate and inform the public on the effects of topical issues experienced in the local community;
3. discuss the need for performing collection of own and/or others music, dance and drama;
4. develop a roadmap for the event (performance): fixing a date, selecting a venue, inviting an audience;
5. select and agree on a theme for the performance by brainstorming, discussing and reaching a consensus;
6. send manual and/or electronic invitations (e.g. letters, postcards, WhatsApp);
7. select own and/or others compositions for the event/performance, by considering factors like creativity and originality, relevance to the theme, social and cultural importance, mode of performance (monologue/solo/group), costumes, props;
8. getting ready: plan the sequence of events, stage/site plan identifying the positions of all facilities (e.g. PA system, lightings, performance zone, entry, exit, changing and makeup rooms/corners);
9. post-performance activities: cleaning, appreciation, appraisal, evaluation, reporting.

1. display portfolio of own visual artworks to educate and inform the public on topical issues in the local community;
2. decide on the types and number of artworks to exhibit and mount them based on the space available and the theme for the exhibition e.g. artworks that best tell the story of the exhibition or theme;
3. assign individual and group tasks and responsibilities and ensure they are carried out successfully e.g. leading visitors through the exhibition space, explaining the concepts/title of the artworks and the theme for the exhibition, writing of comments and signing of visitors' books;
4. display artworks by hanging, draping, placing, spreading, leaning, using plinths to raise or add height and depth to some exhibits;
5. label the works using manual (calligraphy writing) or ICT (computer prints): name of artist, title of work, size of work, and date of production;
6. check/monitor visitors in order to prevent improper practices e.g. touching, lifting, handling and/or taking away some of the exhibits;
7. opening and closing of exhibition;
8. cleaning, appreciation, appraisal, evaluation, reporting etc.

1. watch a video or live performance of music, dance and drama on the culture of the local community;
2. plan to perform some of the music, dance and drama performed during a festival;
3. plan to perform own music, dance and drama compositions to share with, educate and inform the public on own knowledge and understanding of the history and culture of the local community.

1. watch a video or live performances of music, dance and drama on the culture of the local community;
2. plan to perform own music, dance and drama to share with, educate and inform the target audience on things that are topical issues found in the local community;
3. decide on the types and number of performances to perform during the event based on the theme, time available and the expected audience i.e. performances best tell the story or theme of the event;
4. assign individual and group tasks and responsibilities and ensure they are carried out successfully e.g. master of ceremony, ushering and introduction of special guests and other dignitaries to the show (e.g. explaining the concepts/title of the compositions, performances and the theme for the event, recording of comments and suggestions);
5. Sequencing of performances to best tell the story of the event from the beginning to climax;
6. following the programme of the day: opening, performances and closing;
7. cleaning, appreciation, appraisal, evaluation, reporting etc.

1. agree to the guidelines to critically examine and come out with meaning from visual artworks;
2. express own feelings and ideas about own and others' displayed artworks;
3. discuss and accept a guide for appreciating and appraising own and/or others visual artworks based on the guidelines suggested above;
4. identify the correct vocabularies to use for appreciating and appraising artworks;
5. agree on what to use the appraisal report for and how to share it;
6. agree on the approach/method (manual/digital) to use in recording/documenting the appraisal process;
7. fix a day/date for the appreciation/appraisal/jury;
8. select own/others artwork to talk about using the accepted guide.

1. agree on the guidelines to critically examine and come out with meaning of own and others' performed artworks;
2. discuss and accept a guide for appreciating and appraising own and/or others' compositions and performances as suggested above;
3. identify the correct vocabularies to use for appreciating and appraising music, dance and drama;
4. agree on what to use the appraisal report for and how to share it;
5. agree on the approach/method (manual/digital) to use in recording/documenting the appraisal process;
6. fix a day/date for the appreciation/appraisal/jury.

1. view and make informed decisions on agreed guidelines by using the senses and movement;
2. assess based on established guide for judging artworks by using the theme, subject matter, media, techniques, elements;
3. recognise the characteristics of own and others' displayed visual artworks;
4. talk about the usefulness of the displayed visual artworks;
5. identify future modifications that can be made to enhance the usefulness.

1. display (real/photographs/video) selected own and others' displayed visual artworks;
2. talk about the works dispassionately using agreed guidelines;
3. use the outcome of the appreciation/appraisal to modify the product or to produce similar or different artworks;
4. talk about appreciate and appraise own and/or others' visual artworks, using the guidelines above dispassionately;
5. use the outcome of the appreciation/appraisal to modify the product or to produce similar artwork;
6. record/document the activity and share using platform accepted social media by the class/group e.g. Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, WhatsApp etc.

1. based on agreed guidelines assess the value and recognise the characteristics;
2. assess based on established guidelines for judging performing artworks by using the theme, subject matter, media, techniques, elements;
3. express own likes and dislikes about the music, dance and drama artworks;
4. make suggestions for developing own and others' music, dance and drama artworks.

1. display (real/photographs/video) selected own and others' displayed performing artworks;
2. talk about the works dispassionately using agreed guidelines;
3. use the outcome of the appreciation/appraisal to modify the performance or to present similar or different music, dance and drama artwork;
4. talk about appreciate and appraise own and/or others' compositions and performances using the guidelines above dispassionately;
5. use the outcome of the appreciation/appraisal to modify the product or to produce similar or another composition and performance;
6. record/document the activity and share using an accepted social media by the class/group e.g. Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, WhatsApp etc.
